Lewiston School District Officials Announce:
Class of 2020 Parade of Graduates
Lewiston High School & Tammany High School

Lewiston School District, in cooperation with the City of Lewiston and
Lewis Clark State College is excited to announce the Class of 2020 Parade of Graduates on
Saturday, May 30th at 3:00 pm. Staging of the parade route will begin at LCSC, go by
current Lewiston High School, and conclude with awarding diplomas at the new LHS.
Pictures of graduates with their diplomas will be taken as well as a live broadcast of the
event.

District administration and the Board of Directors greatly appreciates the public’s continued
support as we work through this together.

For questions about this notice, please call the Superintendent’s office at 208.748.3043.

PRESS RELEASE - FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

Lewiston School District Officials Announce Limited Public Access

In the interest of public health, effective immediately, public access to all Lewiston School District facilities will be available on a limited basis until further notice. Individuals requiring access to complete business transactions are requested to call ahead to the Lewiston School District Central Services Administrative Office, 208.748.3000, to make the necessary arrangements.

Regular updates to parents and students will continue to be posted to the District website at https://www.lewistonschools.net and to social media.
District administration and the Board of Directors greatly appreciates the public’s continued cooperation as we work through this together.

For questions about this notice, please call the superintendent’s office at 208.748.3043.

post_text:
A letter from Superintendent Dr. Donaldson to Parents

Starting tomorrow, staff will begin or continue the process of touching base with families and students, checking in on their wellbeing and collecting information about possible resource needs that families may have. We know that maintaining the skills and knowledge that students have gained this year is important, and we recognize that remote learning is not the same as homeschooling or in-class learning. As a District, we are committed to rolling out remote learning slowly, as we continue to address the needs of all of our learners. Over the coming weeks, students and families can expect to hear from teachers and staff through calls, texts and online means.

We recognize that showing one another flexibility and grace in these times is even more important than other times, and, working together, we will do our very best to support our children with their education and wellness.

Bob
text:
A letter from Superintendent Dr. Donaldson to Parents

Starting tomorrow, staff will begin or continue the process of touching base with families and students, checking in on their wellbeing and collecting information about possible resource needs that families may have. We know that maintaining the skills and knowledge that students have gained this year is important, and we recognize that remote learning is not the same as homeschooling or in-class learning. As a District, we are committed to rolling out remote learning slowly, as we continue to address the needs of all of our learners. Over the coming weeks, students and families can expect to hear from teachers and staff through calls, texts and online means.

We recognize that showing one another flexibility and grace in these times is even more important than other times, and, working together, we will do our very best to support our children with their education and wellness.

Bob

post_text:
LHS Construction update (10.22.2018)
Accommodations to stabilize the site for winter access around the building continue.
 Water, storm sewer and site lighting is nearly complete in the south parking lot to support prep and
paving - the gravel section and concrete curbing for the south parking lot is now well underway.
 Foundation excavation and under slab work is nearly complete in Area C and continues at Area A.
 Slab on grade placements have commenced in Area C to prepare that area for masonry.
 Masonry continues in the Gymnasium / Athletic wing (Areas E and North D). The main gym box is
topped out minus some infill panels that will be completed once the interior walls are done.
 M, P & E rough-in work is happening as the CMU structure is placed.
 Structural steel, joists and decking are expected to start arriving early-mid November.
text:
LHS Construction update (10.22.2018)
Accommodations to stabilize the site for winter access around the building continue.
 Water, storm sewer and site lighting is nearly complete in the south parking lot to support prep and
paving - the gravel section and concrete curbing for the south parking lot is now well underway.
 Foundation excavation and under slab work is nearly complete in Area C and continues at Area A.
 Slab on grade placements have commenced in Area C to prepare that area for masonry.
 Masonry continues in the Gymnasium / Athletic wing (Areas E and North D). The main gym box is
topped out minus some infill panels that will be completed once the interior walls are done.
 M, P & E rough-in work is happening as the CMU structure is placed.
 Structural steel, joists and decking are expected to start arriving early-mid November.

post_text:
Knights of Columbus donated 400 coats to the school district. These coats will ensure our most neediest students have a warm coat for the upcoming winter season. This is the 9th year Knights of Columbus has donated coats to the school district. Thank you so much for your generosity and supporting our students.

In addition, they also presented a check for $1,500 to go towards stocking the Food Pantry for our students and families.

Helping unload the coats were: Mike Schmidt, Ryan Rosenau, Tom Dougherty, Dave Ellis, Paul Frei, Craig Estes

LHS construction is progressing rapidly! Below is a project update for September 24, 2018:

 Phase 2 grading punch list work has been completed.
 Temporary entrance, roadway and jobsite office / laydown area is established.
 Accommodations for winter access around building will commence in the near future.
 Underground water, storm sewer and site lighting is well underway in the south parking lot to allow
for prep and paving this fall.
 Foundation excavation and under slab work continues in Area C and Area A.
 Foundations and slabs are complete in Area E & North D to support the CMU work.
 Masonry is well underway in the Gymnasium / Athletic wing (Areas E and North D).
 M, P & E rough-in work is being coordinated hand in hand with the CMU walls.
 Shop drawings and coordination are well underway to plan for the steel structure.

post_text:
The Lewiston Board of Directors held a special meeting at noon today to accept a $2 million donation from the DeAtley family in memory of A. Neil DeAtley. Through a Board-adopted resolution, the donation will result in the new Lewiston High School career technical center being named the A. Neil DeAtley Career Technical Education Center. This is the largest donation in the history of the Lewiston School District and as Board President Brad Rice stated, “it is a historic day for our kids”.

We are sincerely grateful to the DeAtley family for this generous legacy gift.
text:
The Lewiston Board of Directors held a special meeting at noon today to accept a $2 million donation from the DeAtley family in memory of A. Neil DeAtley. Through a Board-adopted resolution, the donation will result in the new Lewiston High School career technical center being named the A. Neil DeAtley Career Technical Education Center. This is the largest donation in the history of the Lewiston School District and as Board President Brad Rice stated, “it is a historic day for our kids”.

We are sincerely grateful to the DeAtley family for this generous legacy gift.
